{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":16128,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"a0f414e0-f15e-11e7-b951-c1a9cf7ca6a4","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2018/01/03/wordpress-on-aws-part-3/amp/","params":{},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.66.31","x-forwarded-proto":"https","x-real-ip":"66.249.66.31","host":"bmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{"post":{"slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-3","status":"published","id":"5a4d5340fd55d33f00065ad5","uuid":"628d6232-ea4c-41e1-822c-c6d3462b4c17","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","html":"<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><h1 id=\"settingupourwebinstance\">Setting Up Our Web Instance</h1>\n<p>We will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.</p>\n<p>First let's SSH into our EC2 instance.  To do this you will need to grab the public IP, or public DNS, of your EC2 instance we just created.  You can do this by selecting your EC2 instance from the &quot;Instances&quot; tab on the left.  You can either drag or select those gray boxes on the right to make the bottom pane larger.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2018/01/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.19.06-PM.jpg\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.19.06-PM\"></p>\n<p>Once you have your public IP let's SSH in!  from your favorite SSH tool run the following command (Terminal on Mac or Linux, and I recommend cmder on Windows):</p>\n<p><code>ssh -i mykeylocation.pem ec2-user@mypublicipaddress</code></p>\n<p>If you're on a Mac you may get a warning about permissions.  To fix this you must run the follow command to change the permissions level of your private key:</p>\n<p><code>chmod 400 mykeylocation.pem</code></p>\n<p>Once connect let's elevate to root privileges for this setup (we'll fix the permissions of our website specifically afterwards).</p>\n<p><code>sudo su -</code></p>\n<h2 id=\"installingsoftware\">Installing Software</h2>\n<p>Now that we're logged in let's run the following commands to get all the necessary software onto our EC2 instance.</p>\n<p><code>yum install httpd24</code><br>\n<code>yum install php70</code><br>\n<code>yum install php70-mysql*</code></p>\n<p>You can skip this next step if you would rather connect to your RDS instance using a database tool to create the WordPress user and Database.</p>\n<p><code>yum install mysql</code></p>\n<p>We will also want to install our FTP service.  For this tutorial we'll use vsftp:</p>\n<p><code>yum install vsftpd</code></p>\n<p>Now we will want to make sure when we turn on our instance that Apache is started, so let's run the following command:</p>\n<p><code>chkconfig httpd on</code></p>\n<h2 id=\"configuringoursoftware\">Configuring Our Software</h2>\n<p>Now that we have everything we need installed, let's tweak some settings around.</p>\n<h3 id=\"http\">HTTP</h3>\n<p>First thing since WordPress uses index.php as its main entry point we will need to make sure Apache knows that.  Let's edit our Apache config by running the following:</p>\n<p><code>vim /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf</code></p>\n<p>Find the following block of code:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2018/01/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.50.06-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-10.50.06-PM\"></p>\n<p>I've already added it here, but you will want to make sure index.php is added, otherwise Apache will not look to load it, and you're WordPress site won't load.</p>\n<h3 id=\"vsftp\">VSFTP</h3>\n<p>Here we'll want to open our configuration file:</p>\n<p><code>vim /etc/vsftpd/vsftpd.conf</code></p>\n<p>We will first want to uncomment and change &quot;chroot_local_user&quot; and change it &quot;chroot_local_user=YES&quot;.  This will prevent our FTP user we're about to create from accessing our entire system.</p>\n<p>There we will want to change &quot;anonymous_enable=YES&quot; to &quot;anonymous_enable=NO&quot;. Then let's go down to the bottom of our file and add the following code:</p>\n<pre><code>pasv_enable=YES\npasv_min_port=1024\npasv_max_port=1048\npasv_address=ec2instancePublicIP\n</code></pre>\n<p>Let's save and restart the service:</p>\n<p><code>/etc/init.d/vsftpd restart</code></p>\n<h3 id=\"creatingourlinuxuserforapacheftp\">Creating our Linux User for Apache &amp; FTP</h3>\n<p>Now we're going to create a user which we will user for our WordPress site, to log into FTP.</p>\n<p><code>adduser wpuser</code></p>\n<p>Then we will set the password (make sure to save this) for our new user.</p>\n<p><code>passwd wpuser</code></p>\n<p>Now as mentioned before, we've prevent our ftp user from accessing our entire system, so we'll want to change its home directory. To do that we will run:</p>\n<p><code>usermod -d /var/www/html/ wpuser</code></p>\n<p>This will set our wpuser home directory to the location where we will be serving our WordPress blog.</p>\n<h2 id=\"downloadingandsettingupwordpress\">Downloading and Setting up WordPress</h2>\n<p>Here we'll get our WordPress install to &quot;/var/www/html/&quot; and get our permissions setup.  First let's download the latest version of WordPress and extract it to our web folder:</p>\n<p><code>wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz</code><br>\n<code>tar -xzf latest.tar.gz</code></p>\n<p>Now when we type ls we should see our &quot;wordpress&quot; folder. Let's move its contents into our html folder.</p>\n<p><code>mv wordpress/* /var/www/html/</code></p>\n<p>Now that we got it at the right location let's change directories there and start working on our site.</p>\n<p><code>cd /var/www/html</code></p>\n<p>Now that we're here we need to change permissions so that our user and apache can access this folder:</p>\n<p><code>chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html</code></p>\n<p>This command will make wpuser the owner and change the group to apache.</p>\n<h3 id=\"editingthewordpressconfig\">Editing the WordPress Config</h3>\n<p>Now that we have that let's make a copy of the wp-config-sample.php and bring it to our active config and edit it.</p>\n<p><code>cp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php</code><br>\n<code>vim wp-config.php</code></p>\n<p>There are 4 variables that we'll be changing there.</p>\n<pre><code>/** The name of the database for WordPress */\ndefine('DB_NAME', 'wpblog');\n\n/** MySQL database username */\ndefine('DB_USER', 'wpblogger');\n\n/** MySQL database password */\ndefine('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');\n\n/** MySQL hostname */\ndefine('DB_HOST', 'myrdsprivatehostname');\n</code></pre>\n<p>We'll be create the user and password in just a sec, but you can grab myrdsprivatehostname (Endpoint) from the RDS page in the AWS console.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2018/01/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.42.54-PM.jpg\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.42.54-PM\"></p>\n<p>We've already allowed our EC2 Security group to connect to our RDS instance so we should be good!</p>\n<p>Now we need to create the database on our RDS instance and database user that will have permissions to it.  Let's connect to our RDS endpoint by issuing the following command:</p>\n<p><code>mysql -u root -p -h endpoint</code></p>\n<p>Replace endpoint with the endpoint we copied earlier. You will now be prompted for a password. This password will be the root password from when we setup our RDS instance.</p>\n<pre><code>CREATE DATABASE wpblog;\nCREATE USER wpblogger;\nGRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON wpblog.* To 'wpblogger'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'password';\nflush privileges;\n</code></pre>\n<p>From this point we should be good to go, assuming all of our settings are right.  One last thing, since we copied our wp-config.php with our root user we will need to do the following again.</p>\n<p><code>chown -R apache:apache /var/www/html</code></p>\n<h1 id=\"wrappingup\">Wrapping Up</h1>\n<p>You should now be able to access your WordPress setup page from your EC2 instance public IP.  Go through the typical Wordpress prompts, but afterwards you should have a working WordPress site running off of Amazon EC2 and RDS!</p>\n<p>If you have any questions, notice some errors, or typos on my part; let me know in the comments!</p>\n</div>","feature_image":"/content/images/2018/01/Untitled-3.png","featured":false,"page":false,"locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 3","meta_description":"We will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM.","created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","published_at":{},"published_by":"1","custom_excerpt":"We will be configuring our web VM with Apache 2.4, PHP 7.0.  In addition, for simplicity, we will install the default MySQL package on our VM as this will allow us to later connect to our RDS instance and create the WP User and Database for our site.","codeinjection_head":"","codeinjection_foot":"","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"custom_template":null,"tags":{"0":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"1":{"id":"5a45c050fd55d33f00065ac5","name":"RDS","slug":"rds","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"2":{"id":"5a4